<h5><b> Rules Of Badminton </b></h5>
<p>
	<p>The best of three games, each worth 21 points, constitutes a match.</p>

    <p>A rally is scored as one point for the player or couple that wins it.</p>

    <p>At 20 all, the game is won by the person or couple that first takes a 2-point advantage.</p>

    <p>The team scoring the 30th point wins the match when the score is 29 all.</p>

    <p>In the next game, the player or winning pair gets the first serve.</p>

    <p>In a badminton match, either two opponents (singles) or four opponents (doubles) compete (doubles).</p>

    <p>The official court measurements must be used to play a competitive match inside.</p>

    <p>If the returned shuttlecock hits the net or lands outside of the court, the player loses the point.</p>

    <p>A point is scored when the shuttlecock lands inside the opponent's court.</p>

    <p>The server and receiver begin the rally by positioning themselves on diagonally opposite service courts.</p>

    <p>A valid serve must be delivered diagonally across the court and over the net.</p>

    <p>A badminton serve must be struck beneath the server's waist and under his or her arm.</p>

    <p>When the server hits the shuttle, the entire shuttle should be less than 1.15 metres off the court's surface, with the racquet shaft facing downward.</p>

    <p>It is not permitted for the shuttlecock to bounce.</p>

    <p>The players will proceed to the opposing serving stations for the following point once a point has been won.</p>  
